 notably Kant, Hegel, Horkheimer, and Habermas—as well as with a variety of contemporary Anglo-American thinkers such as Richard Rorty, Stanley Cavell, John McDowell, and Robert Pippin—he illuminates Adorno’s important revisions to this fraught concept and how his different understanding of autonomous agency, fully articulated, might open up new and positive social and political possibilities. Altogether, Autonomy after Auschwitz is a meditation on modern evil and human agency, one that demonstrates the tremendous ethical stakes at the heart of philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAutonomy (Philosophy) 0aAutonomy (Philosophy). 0aPhilosophy, German. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  agermany, german, 20th century, modernity, modernism, auschwitz, philosophy, autonomy, idealism, human freedom, free, humanity, theodor adorno, immanuel kant, georg wilhelm friedrich hegel, max horkheimer, habermas, autonomous agency, ethical, ethics, morality, morals, dialectic of enlightenment, historical, history, myth, subjectivity, reason, expression, discussion, spirit, sociology, psychology, critical theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022615548740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226155517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226155517/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles